Typedef Documentation

typedef UINT8 DataConnProfileId
 

DataConnProfileId is the type of a data connection identifier. A DataConnProfileId is a unique value assigned to a specific DataConnProfile at creation time. It is very unlikely that two profiles will be assigned the same identifier.

typedef DataConnProfileId DataConnProfileIdSet[c_data_conn_profile_count]
 

DataConnProfileIdSet is a set of data connection profile identifiers.

enum SocketError
 

SocketError defines APOXI socket specific error codes and standard BSD socket error codes. For further details about BSD socket error codes please refer to the Berkeley socket documentation.

Enumerator:
c_socket_no_error  No error.

-- APOXI specific socket error codes --.
c_socket_unknown_error  Unknown error of system sockets.
c_socket_no_bearer  No bearer for data connection available.
c_socket_bearer_busy  Requested bearer is busy with a differing data connection.
c_socket_bearer_not_supported  Requested bearer is not supported.
c_socket_fatal_system_error  Fatal system error, i.e. something is completely messed up.
c_socket_wrong_execution_context  Request done by a differing execution context.
c_socket_subsystem_not_init  Socket subsystem is not initialized yet.
c_socket_no_data_conn_profile  Specified data connection profile not found.
c_socket_conn_setup_failed  Data connection setup failed.
c_socket_conn_in_release  Data connection setup failed as previous connection has not yet finished release.
c_socket_conn_in_setup  Data connection is getting set up right now.
c_socket_conn_blocked  Data connection is blocked.
c_socket_conn_perform_setup  Data connection has to be setup by this socket.
c_socket_conn_timed_out  Data connection timed out.
c_socket_conn_lost  Data connection lost.
c_socket_wait_for_send_unblocked  Waiting for the send control message was unblocked.
c_socket_wait_for_recv_unblocked  Waiting for the receive control message was unblocked.

-- BSD specific socket error codes --.
c_socket_ebadf  Bad socket file descriptor.
c_socket_eintr  Interrupted function call.
A blocking operation was interrupted.
c_socket_einval  Invalid argument passed.
Some invalid argument was supplied (for example, specifying an invalid level to the setsockopt function). In some instances, it also refers to the current state of the socket, for instance, calling accept on a socket that is not listening.
c_socket_enotsock  Socket operation on nonsocket.
An operation was attempted on something that is not a socket or on an invalid (i.e. not open) socket.
c_socket_eopnotsupp  Operation not supported.
The attempted operation is not supported for the type of object referenced.
c_socket_ewouldblock  Resource temporarily unavailable.
This error is returned from operations on nonblocking sockets that cannot be completed immediately. It is a nonfatal error, and the operation should be retried later.
c_socket_eaddrnotavail  Cannot assign requested address.
The requested address is not valid in its context. This normally results from an attempt to bind to an address that is not valid for the local machine.
c_socket_eacces  Permission denied.
An attempt was made to access a socket in a way forbidden by its access permissions. An example is using a broadcast address for sendto without broadcast permission being set using setsockopt(SO_BROADCAST).
c_socket_eisconn  Socket is already connected.
A connect request was made on an already-connected socket. Some implementations also return this error if sendto is called on a connected SOCK_DGRAM socket (for SOCK_STREAM sockets, the to parameter in sendto is ignored) although other implementations treat this as a legal occurrence.
c_socket_etimedout  Connection timed out.
A connect or send request failed because the connected party did not properly respond after a period of time. The timeout period is dependent on the communication protocol.
c_socket_econnrefused  Connection refused.
No connection could be made because the target machine actively refused it. This usually results from trying to connect to a service that is inactive on the foreign host.
c_socket_enetunreach  Network is unreachable.
A socket operation was attempted to an unreachable network.
c_socket_eaddrinuse  Address already in use.
Only one usage of each socket address (protocol/IP address/port) is permitted.
c_socket_ealready  Operation already in progress.
An operation was attempted on a non-blocking object that already had an operation in progress.
c_socket_einprogress  Operation now in progress.
An operation that takes a long time to complete (such as a) was attempted on a non-blocking socket.
c_socket_enotconn  Socket is not connected.
A request to send or receive data was disallowed because the socket is not connected and (when sending on a datagram socket) no address was supplied.
c_socket_emsgsize  Message too long.
A message sent on a socket was larger than the internal message buffer or some other network limit.
c_socket_enobufs  No buffer space available.
An operation on a socket or pipe was not performed because the system lacked sufficient buffer space or because a queue was full.
c_socket_enoprotoopt  Bad protocol option.
An unknown, invalid or unsupported option or level was specified in a getsockopt or setsockopt call.
c_socket_emfile  Too many open sockets.
Too many open sockets. Each implementation may have a maximum number of socket handles available, either globally, per process, or per thread.
c_socket_econnreset  Connection reset by peer.
A connection was forcibly closed by a peer. This normally results from a loss of the connection on the remote socket due to a timeout or a reboot.
c_socket_ehostunreach  No route to host.
A socket operation was attempted to an unreachable host.
c_socket_econnaborted  Software caused connection abort.
A connection abort was caused internal to your host machine. The software caused a connection abort because there is no space on the socket's queue and the socket cannot receive further connections.
c_socket_efault  Bad address.
The system detected an invalid address in attempting to use an argument of a call.
c_socket_edestaddrreq  Destination address required.
A required address was omitted from an operation on a socket.
c_socket_eprototype  Protocol wrong type for socket.
A protocol was specified that does not support the semantics of the socket type requested. For example, you cannot use the internet UDP protocol with type SOCK_STREAM.
c_socket_eprotonosupport  Protocol not supported.
The protocol has not been configured into the system, or no implementation for it exists.
c_socket_esocktnosupport  Socket type not supported.
The support for the socket type has not been configured into the system or no implementation for it exists.
c_socket_epfnosupport  Protocol family not supported.
The protocol family has not been configured into the system or no implementation for it exists.
c_socket_eafnosupport  Address family not supported by protocol family.
An address incompatible with the requested protocol was used. For example, you shouldn't necessarily expect to be able to use NS addresses with ARPA Internet protocols.
c_socket_enetdown  Network is down.
A socket operation encountered a dead network.
c_socket_enetreset  Network dropped connection on reset.
The host you were connected to crashed and rebooted.
c_socket_eshutdown  Cannot send after socket shutdown.
A request to send data was disallowed because the socket had already been shut down.
c_socket_ehostdown  Host is down.
A socket operation failed because the destination host was down. A socket operation encountered a dead host. Networking activity on the local host has not been initiated.

c_invalid_data_conn_profile_id defines invalid value of a DataConnProfileId

const DataConnProfileId c_max_data_conn_profile_id = (1 << (sizeof(DataConnProfileId) * 8 - 1)) - 1
 

c_max_data_conn_profile_id defines the upper bound ID a non-temporary data connection profile can get. The range of data connection profile IDs is shared between persistent and temporary data connection profiles, and one value is defined as the invalid data connection profile ID (see c_invalid_data_conn_profile_id).

The whole range is splitted like that: + 0 : the invalid data connection profile ID + 1 .. 127 : range for persistent data connection profile IDs + 128 .. 255 : range for temporary data connection profile IDs

const UINT c_max_inet_socket_count = APOXI_MAX_INET_SOCKET_COUNT
 

c_max_inet_socket_count specifies the maximum number of InetSockets in parallel.
